			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2022</a> paper:</span><br><i>Workbench for Creating Block-Based Environments</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MauricioVeranoMerino.html">Mauricio Verano Merino</a>, <a href="../profile/KoenvanWijk.html">Koen van Wijk</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3567512.3567518">10.1145/3567512.3567518</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It presents a workbench to build block-based programming environments.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> Block-based environments are visual languages and the work targets their visual tooling.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> The goal is to support usable, end-user-friendly editing and interaction.
</li></ul></li></ul>
